 105     @classmethod
 106     def from_pipfile(cls, name, pipfile):
 107         attr_fields = [field.name for field in attr.fields(cls)]
 108         found_keys = [k for k in pipfile.keys() if k in attr_fields]
 109         marker_strings = ["{0} {1}".format(k, pipfile[k]) for k in found_keys]
 110         if pipfile.get("markers"):
 111             marker_strings.append(pipfile.get("markers"))
 112         markers = set()
 113         for marker in marker_strings:
 114             markers.add(marker)
 115         combined_marker = None
 116         try:
 117             combined_marker = cls.make_marker(" and ".join(sorted(markers)))
 118         except RequirementError:
 119             pass
 120         else:
 121             return combined_marker

 124 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 125 def _tuplize_version(version):
 126     # type: (STRING_TYPE) -> Tuple[int, ...]
 127     return tuple(int(x) for x in filter(lambda i: i != "*", version.split(".")))

 130 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 131 def _format_version(version):
 132     # type: (Tuple[int, ...]) -> STRING_TYPE
 133     if not isinstance(version, six.string_types):
 134         return ".".join(str(i) for i in version)
 135     return version

 138 # Prefer [x,y) ranges.
 139 REPLACE_RANGES = {">": ">=", "<=": "<"}
 140 
 141 
 142 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 143 def _format_pyspec(specifier):
 144     # type: (Union[STRING_TYPE, Specifier]) -> Specifier
 145     if isinstance(specifier, str):
 146         if not any(op in specifier for op in Specifier._operators.keys()):
 147             specifier = "=={0}".format(specifier)
 148         specifier = Specifier(specifier)
 149     version = getattr(specifier, "version", specifier).rstrip()
 150     if version and version.endswith("*"):
 151         if version.endswith(".*"):
 152             version = version[:-2]
 153         version = version.rstrip("*")
 154         specifier = Specifier("{0}{1}".format(specifier.operator, version))
 155     try:
 156         op = REPLACE_RANGES[specifier.operator]
 157     except KeyError:
 158         return specifier
 159     curr_tuple = _tuplize_version(version)
 160     try:
 161         next_tuple = (curr_tuple[0], curr_tuple[1] + 1)
 162     except IndexError:
 163         next_tuple = (curr_tuple[0], 1)
 164     if not next_tuple[1] <= MAX_VERSIONS[next_tuple[0]]:
 165         if specifier.operator == "<" and curr_tuple[1] <= MAX_VERSIONS[next_tuple[0]]:
 166             op = "<="
 167             next_tuple = (next_tuple[0], curr_tuple[1])
 168         else:
 169             return specifier
 170     specifier = Specifier("{0}{1}".format(op, _format_version(next_tuple)))
 171     return specifier

 174 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 175 def _get_specs(specset):
 176     if specset is None:
 177         return
 178     if is_instance(specset, Specifier):
 179         new_specset = SpecifierSet()
 180         specs = set()
 181         specs.add(specset)
 182         new_specset._specs = frozenset(specs)
 183         specset = new_specset
 184     if isinstance(specset, str):
 185         specset = SpecifierSet(specset)
 186     result = []
 187     for spec in set(specset):
 188         version = spec.version
 189         op = spec.operator
 190         if op in ("in", "not in"):
 191             versions = version.split(",")
 192             op = "==" if op == "in" else "!="
 193             for ver in versions:
 194                 result.append((op, _tuplize_version(ver.strip())))
 195         else:
 196             result.append((spec.operator, _tuplize_version(spec.version)))
 197     return sorted(result, key=operator.itemgetter(1))
 198

 200 # TODO: Rename this to something meaningful
 201 def _group_by_op(specs):
 202     # type: (Union[Set[Specifier], SpecifierSet]) -> Iterator
 203     specs = [_get_specs(x) for x in list(specs)]
 204     flattened = [
 205         ((op, len(version) > 2), version) for spec in specs for op, version in spec
 206     ]
 207     specs = sorted(flattened)
 208     grouping = itertools.groupby(specs, key=operator.itemgetter(0))
 209     return grouping

 212 # TODO: rename this to something meaningful
 213 def normalize_specifier_set(specs):
 214     # type: (Union[str, SpecifierSet]) -> Optional[Set[Specifier]]
 215     """Given a specifier set, a string, or an iterable, normalize the specifiers
 216 
 217     .. note:: This function exists largely to deal with ``pyzmq`` which handles
 218         the ``requires_python`` specifier incorrectly, using ``3.7*`` rather than
 219         the correct form of ``3.7.*``.  This workaround can likely go away if
 220         we ever introduce enforcement for metadata standards on PyPI.
 221 
 222     :param Union[str, SpecifierSet] specs: Supplied specifiers to normalize
 223     :return: A new set of specifiers or specifierset
 224     :rtype: Union[Set[Specifier], :class:`~packaging.specifiers.SpecifierSet`]
 225     """
 226     if not specs:
 227         return None
 228     if isinstance(specs, set):
 229         return specs
 230     # when we aren't dealing with a string at all, we can normalize this as usual
 231     elif not isinstance(specs, six.string_types):
 232         return {_format_pyspec(spec) for spec in specs}
 233     spec_list = []
 234     for spec in specs.split(","):
 235         spec = spec.strip()
 236         if spec.endswith(".*"):
 237             spec = spec[:-2]
 238         spec = spec.rstrip("*")
 239         spec_list.append(spec)
 240     return normalize_specifier_set(SpecifierSet(",".join(spec_list)))

 245 def get_sorted_version_string(version_set):
 246     # type: (Set[AnyStr]) -> AnyStr
 247     version_list = sorted(

 254 # TODO: Rename this to something meaningful
 255 # TODO: Add a deprecation decorator and deprecate this -- i'm sure it's used
 256 # in other libraries
 257 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 258 def cleanup_pyspecs(specs, joiner="or"):
 259     specs = normalize_specifier_set(specs)
 260     # for != operator we want to group by version
 261     # if all are consecutive, join as a list
 262     results = {}
 263     translation_map = {
 264         # if we are doing an or operation, we need to use the min for >=
 265         # this way OR(>=2.6, >=2.7, >=3.6) picks >=2.6
 266         # if we do an AND operation we need to use MAX to be more selective
 267         (">", ">="): {
 268             "or": lambda x: _format_version(min(x)),
 269             "and": lambda x: _format_version(max(x)),
 270         },
 271         # we use inverse logic here so we will take the max value if we are
 272         # using OR but the min value if we are using AND
 273         ("<", "<="): {
 274             "or": lambda x: _format_version(max(x)),
 275             "and": lambda x: _format_version(min(x)),
 276         },
 277         # leave these the same no matter what operator we use
 278         ("!=", "==", "~=", "==="): {
 279             "or": get_sorted_version_string,
 280             "and": get_sorted_version_string,
 281         },
 282     }
 283     op_translations = {
 284         "!=": lambda x: "not in" if len(x) > 1 else "!=",
 285         "==": lambda x: "in" if len(x) > 1 else "==",
 286     }
 287     translation_keys = list(translation_map.keys())
 288     for op_and_version_type, versions in _group_by_op(tuple(specs)):
 289         op = op_and_version_type[0]
 290         versions = [version[1] for version in versions]
 291         versions = sorted(dedup(versions))
 292         op_key = next(iter(k for k in translation_keys if op in k), None)
 293         version_value = versions
 294         if op_key is not None:
 295             version_value = translation_map[op_key][joiner](versions)
 296         if op in op_translations:
 297             op = op_translations[op](versions)
 298         results[(op, op_and_version_type[1])] = version_value
 299     return sorted([(k[0], v) for k, v in results.items()], key=operator.itemgetter(1))

 302 # TODO: Rename this to something meaningful
 303 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 304 def fix_version_tuple(version_tuple):
 305     # type: (Tuple[AnyStr, AnyStr]) -> Tuple[AnyStr, AnyStr]
 306     op, version = version_tuple
 307     max_major = max(MAX_VERSIONS.keys())
 308     if version[0] > max_major:
 309         return (op, (max_major, MAX_VERSIONS[max_major]))
 310     max_allowed = MAX_VERSIONS[version[0]]
 311     if op == "<" and version[1] > max_allowed and version[1] - 1 <= max_allowed:
 312         op = "<="
 313         version = (version[0], version[1] - 1)
 314     return (op, version)

 317 # TODO: Rename this to something meaningful, deprecate it (See prior function)
 318 @lru_cache(maxsize=128)
 319 def get_versions(specset, group_by_operator=True):
 320     # type: (Union[Set[Specifier], SpecifierSet], bool) -> List[Tuple[STRING_TYPE, STRING_TYPE]]
 321     specs = [_get_specs(x) for x in list(tuple(specset))]
 322     initial_sort_key = lambda k: (k[0], k[1])
 323     initial_grouping_key = operator.itemgetter(0)
 324     if not group_by_operator:
 325         initial_grouping_key = operator.itemgetter(1)
 326         initial_sort_key = operator.itemgetter(1)
 327     version_tuples = sorted(
 328         set((op, version) for spec in specs for op, version in spec), key=initial_sort_key
 329     )
 330     version_tuples = [fix_version_tuple(t) for t in version_tuples]
 331     op_groups = [
 332         (grp, list(map(operator.itemgetter(1), keys)))
 333         for grp, keys in itertools.groupby(version_tuples, key=initial_grouping_key)
 334     ]
 335     versions = [
 336         (op, packaging.version.parse(".".join(str(v) for v in val)))
 337         for op, vals in op_groups
 338         for val in vals
 339     ]
 340     return sorted(versions, key=operator.itemgetter(1))

 365     return _strip_marker_elem("python_version", elements)

 367 
 368 def _strip_marker_elem(elem_name, elements):
 369     """Remove the supplied element from the marker.
 370 
 371     This is not a comprehensive implementation, but relies on an important
 372     characteristic of metadata generation: The element's operand is always
 373     associated with an "and" operator. This means that we can simply remove the
 374     operand and the "and" operator associated with it.
 375     """
 376 
 377     extra_indexes = []
 378     preceding_operators = ["and"] if elem_name == "extra" else ["and", "or"]
 379     for i, element in enumerate(elements):
 380         if isinstance(element, list):
 381             cancelled = _strip_marker_elem(elem_name, element)
 382             if cancelled:
 383                 extra_indexes.append(i)
 384         elif isinstance(element, tuple) and element[0].value == elem_name:
 385             extra_indexes.append(i)
 386     for i in reversed(extra_indexes):
 387         del elements[i]
 388         if i > 0 and elements[i - 1] in preceding_operators:
 389             # Remove the "and" before it.
 390             del elements[i - 1]
 391         elif elements:
 392             # This shouldn't ever happen, but is included for completeness.
 393             # If there is not an "and" before this element, try to remove the
 394             # operator after it.
 395             del elements[0]
 396     return not elements

 399 def _get_stripped_marker(marker, strip_func):
 400     """Build a new marker which is cleaned according to `strip_func`"""
 401 
 402     if not marker:
 403         return None
 404     marker = _ensure_marker(marker)
 405     elements = marker._markers
 406     strip_func(elements)
 407     if elements:
 408         return marker
 409     return None

 435 def _markers_collect_extras(markers, collection):
 436     # Optimization: the marker element is usually appended at the end.
 437     for el in reversed(markers):
 438         if isinstance(el, tuple) and el[0].value == "extra" and el[1].value == "==":
 439             collection.add(el[2].value)
 440         elif isinstance(el, list):
 441             _markers_collect_extras(el, collection)
 442 
 443 
 444 def _markers_collect_pyversions(markers, collection):
 445     local_collection = []
 446     marker_format_str = "{0}"
 447     for i, el in enumerate(reversed(markers)):
 448         if isinstance(el, tuple) and el[0].value == "python_version":
 449             new_marker = str(gen_marker(el))
 450             local_collection.append(marker_format_str.format(new_marker))
 451         elif isinstance(el, list):
 452             _markers_collect_pyversions(el, local_collection)
 453     if local_collection:
 454         # local_collection = "{0}".format(" ".join(local_collection))
 455         collection.extend(local_collection)

 458 def _markers_contains_extra(markers):
 459     # Optimization: the marker element is usually appended at the end.
 460     return _markers_contains_key(markers, "extra")
 461 
 462 
 463 def _markers_contains_pyversion(markers):
 464     return _markers_contains_key(markers, "python_version")
 465 
 466 
 467 def _markers_contains_key(markers, key):
 468     for element in reversed(markers):
 469         if isinstance(element, tuple) and element[0].value == key:
 470             return True
 471         elif isinstance(element, list):
 472             if _markers_contains_key(element, key):
 473                 return True
 474     return False

 477 @lru_cache(maxsize=128)
 478 def get_contained_extras(marker):
 479     """Collect "extra == ..." operands from a marker.
 480 
 481     Returns a list of str. Each str is a speficied extra in this marker.
 482     """
 483     if not marker:
 484         return set()
 485     extras = set()
 486     marker = _ensure_marker(marker)
 487     _markers_collect_extras(marker._markers, extras)
 488     return extras

 490 
 491 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 492 def get_contained_pyversions(marker):
 493     """Collect all `python_version` operands from a marker.
 494     """
 495 
 496     collection = []
 497     if not marker:
 498         return set()
 499     marker = _ensure_marker(marker)
 500     # Collect the (Variable, Op, Value) tuples and string joiners from the marker
 501     _markers_collect_pyversions(marker._markers, collection)
 502     marker_str = " and ".join(sorted(collection))
 503     if not marker_str:
 504         return set()
 505     # Use the distlib dictionary parser to create a dictionary 'trie' which is a bit
 506     # easier to reason about
 507     marker_dict = distlib.markers.parse_marker(marker_str)[0]
 508     version_set = set()
 509     pyversions, _ = parse_marker_dict(marker_dict)
 510     if isinstance(pyversions, set):
 511         version_set.update(pyversions)
 512     elif pyversions is not None:
 513         version_set.add(pyversions)
 514     # Each distinct element in the set was separated by an "and" operator in the marker
 515     # So we will need to reduce them with an intersection here rather than a union
 516     # in order to find the boundaries
 517     versions = set()
 518     if version_set:
 519         versions = reduce(lambda x, y: x & y, version_set)
 520     return versions
 521

 544 def _split_specifierset_str(specset_str, prefix="=="):
 545     # type: (str, str) -> Set[Specifier]
 546     """
 547     Take a specifierset string and split it into a list to join for specifier sets
 548 
 549     :param str specset_str: A string containing python versions, often comma separated
 550     :param str prefix: A prefix to use when generating the specifier set
 551     :return: A list of :class:`Specifier` instances generated with the provided prefix
 552     :rtype: Set[Specifier]
 553     """
 554     specifiers = set()
 555     if "," not in specset_str and " " in specset_str:
 556         values = [v.strip() for v in specset_str.split()]
 557     else:
 558         values = [v.strip() for v in specset_str.split(",")]
 559     if prefix == "!=" and any(v in values for v in DEPRECATED_VERSIONS):
 560         values += DEPRECATED_VERSIONS[:]
 561     for value in sorted(values):
 562         specifiers.add(Specifier("{0}{1}".format(prefix, value)))
 563     return specifiers
 564 
 565 
 566 def _get_specifiers_from_markers(marker_item):
 567     """
 568     Given a marker item, get specifiers from the version marker
 569 
 570     :param :class:`~packaging.markers.Marker` marker_sequence: A marker describing a version constraint
 571     :return: A set of specifiers corresponding to the marker constraint
 572     :rtype: Set[Specifier]
 573     """
 574     specifiers = set()
 575     if isinstance(marker_item, tuple):
 576         variable, op, value = marker_item
 577         if variable.value != "python_version":
 578             return specifiers
 579         if op.value == "in":
 580             specifiers.update(_split_specifierset_str(value.value, prefix="=="))
 581         elif op.value == "not in":
 582             specifiers.update(_split_specifierset_str(value.value, prefix="!="))
 583         else:
 584             specifiers.add(Specifier("{0}{1}".format(op.value, value.value)))
 585     elif isinstance(marker_item, list):
 586         parts = get_specset(marker_item)
 587         if parts:
 588             specifiers.update(parts)
 589     return specifiers
 590 
 591 
 592 def get_specset(marker_list):
 593     # type: (List) -> Optional[SpecifierSet]
 594     specset = set()
 595     _last_str = "and"
 596     for marker_parts in marker_list:
 597         if isinstance(marker_parts, str):
 598             _last_str = marker_parts  # noqa
 599         else:
 600             specset.update(_get_specifiers_from_markers(marker_parts))
 601     specifiers = SpecifierSet()
 602     specifiers._specs = frozenset(specset)
 603     return specifiers

 606 # TODO: Refactor this (reduce complexity)
 607 def parse_marker_dict(marker_dict):
 608     op = marker_dict["op"]
 609     lhs = marker_dict["lhs"]
 610     rhs = marker_dict["rhs"]
 611     # This is where the spec sets for each side land if we have an "or" operator
 612     side_spec_list = []
 613     side_markers_list = []
 614     finalized_marker = ""
 615     # And if we hit the end of the parse tree we use this format string to make a marker
 616     format_string = "{lhs} {op} {rhs}"
 617     specset = SpecifierSet()
 618     specs = set()
 619     # Essentially we will iterate over each side of the parsed marker if either one is
 620     # A mapping instance (i.e. a dictionary) and recursively parse and reduce the specset
 621     # Union the "and" specs, intersect the "or"s to find the most appropriate range
 622     if any(issubclass(type(side), Mapping) for side in (lhs, rhs)):
 623         for side in (lhs, rhs):
 624             side_specs = set()
 625             side_markers = set()
 626             if issubclass(type(side), Mapping):
 627                 merged_side_specs, merged_side_markers = parse_marker_dict(side)
 628                 side_specs.update(merged_side_specs)
 629                 side_markers.update(merged_side_markers)
 630             else:
 631                 marker = _ensure_marker(side)
 632                 marker_parts = getattr(marker, "_markers", [])
 633                 if marker_parts[0][0].value == "python_version":
 634                     side_specs |= set(get_specset(marker_parts))
 635                 else:
 636                     side_markers.add(str(marker))
 637             side_spec_list.append(side_specs)
 638             side_markers_list.append(side_markers)
 639         if op == "and":
 640             # When we are "and"-ing things together, it probably makes the most sense
 641             # to reduce them here into a single PySpec instance
 642             specs = reduce(lambda x, y: set(x) | set(y), side_spec_list)
 643             markers = reduce(lambda x, y: set(x) | set(y), side_markers_list)
 644             if not specs and not markers:
 645                 return specset, finalized_marker
 646             if markers and isinstance(markers, (tuple, list, Set)):
 647                 finalized_marker = Marker(" and ".join([m for m in markers if m]))
 648             elif markers:
 649                 finalized_marker = str(markers)
 650             specset._specs = frozenset(specs)
 651             return specset, finalized_marker
 652         # Actually when we "or" things as well we can also just turn them into a reduced
 653         # set using this logic now
 654         sides = reduce(lambda x, y: set(x) & set(y), side_spec_list)
 655         finalized_marker = " or ".join(
 656             [normalize_marker_str(m) for m in side_markers_list]
 657         )
 658         specset._specs = frozenset(sorted(sides))
 659         return specset, finalized_marker
 660     else:
 661         # At the tip of the tree we are dealing with strings all around and they just need
 662         # to be smashed together
 663         specs = set()
 664         if lhs == "python_version":
 665             format_string = "{lhs}{op}{rhs}"
 666             marker = Marker(format_string.format(**marker_dict))
 667             marker_parts = getattr(marker, "_markers", [])
 668             _set = get_specset(marker_parts)
 669             if _set:
 670                 specs |= set(_set)
 671                 specset._specs = frozenset(specs)
 672         return specset, finalized_marker
 673 
 674 
 675 def _contains_micro_version(version_string):
 676     return re.search("\d+\.\d+\.\d+", version_string) is not None
 677 
 678 
 679 def format_pyversion(parts):
 680     op, val = parts
 681     version_marker = (
 682         "python_full_version" if _contains_micro_version(val) else "python_version"
 683     )
 684     return "{0} {1} '{2}'".format(version_marker, op, val)
 685 
 686 
 687 def normalize_marker_str(marker):
 688     # type: (Union[Marker, STRING_TYPE]) -> str
 689     marker_str = ""
 690     if not marker:
 691         return None
 692     if not is_instance(marker, Marker):
 693         marker = _ensure_marker(marker)
 694     pyversion = get_contained_pyversions(marker)
 695     marker = get_without_pyversion(marker)
 696     if pyversion:
 697         parts = cleanup_pyspecs(pyversion)
 698         marker_str = " and ".join([format_pyversion(pv) for pv in parts])
 699     if marker:
 700         if marker_str:
 701             marker_str = "{0!s} and {1!s}".format(marker_str, marker)
 702         else:
 703             marker_str = "{0!s}".format(marker)
 704     return marker_str.replace('"', "'")
 705 
 706 
 707 @lru_cache(maxsize=1024)
 708 def marker_from_specifier(spec):
 709     # type: (STRING_TYPE) -> Marker
 710     if not any(spec.startswith(k) for k in Specifier._operators.keys()):
 711         if spec.strip().lower() in ["any", "<any>", "*"]:
 712             return None
 713         spec = "=={0}".format(spec)
 714     elif spec.startswith("==") and spec.count("=") > 3:
 715         spec = "=={0}".format(spec.lstrip("="))
 716     if not spec:
 717         return None
 718     marker_segments = []
 719     for marker_segment in cleanup_pyspecs(spec):
 720         marker_segments.append(format_pyversion(marker_segment))
 721     marker_str = " and ".join(marker_segments).replace('"', "'")
 722     return Marker(marker_str)
 723 
 724 
 725 def merge_markers(m1, m2):
 726     # type: (Marker, Marker) -> Optional[Marker]
 727     if not all((m1, m2)):
 728         return next(iter(v for v in (m1, m2) if v), None)
 729     m1 = _ensure_marker(m1)
 730     m2 = _ensure_marker(m2)
 731     _markers = []  # type: List[Marker]
 732     for marker in (m1, m2):
 733         _markers.append(str(marker))
 734     marker_str = " and ".join([normalize_marker_str(m) for m in _markers if m])
 735     return _ensure_marker(normalize_marker_str(marker_str))
